I waited and shortly after another customer arrived. They attended her right away, therefore she is a regular, I was noticed, but ignored. I eventually left, and had a random number contact me via text. One of the employees apparently texted me, threating me to not come back, like if I even wanted to. On a call she told my girlfriend it was all my fault, obviously not wanting to own up to her mistake. She told her a different story which I find comic because not once did we exchange any words. Yet she was rapid to blame me and even though
she ignored me, knew exactly who I was.I'm not here to talk down on anyone, but please improve your service and learn to take responsibility. Also, mis raices is down a few blocks. Their food is better and cheaper, and they actually pay attention to the customers.  Just saying.< /Review>

Unbelievable I would post a 5 star review for a gas station/convenience store, but after traveling the northern to southern CA route so many times, with so many stops at icky gas stations for a restroom and a snack, I can honestly say this was the best stop. Hotels.com reviewer< /username>
<user>None< /user>< text>
The room was the last one available. Was an adjoining  room nicely done comfy Murphy bed. Equipped with Mini frig, microwave and coffee maker.  NO Utensils in room. Shared kitchen down stairs is well equipped  with gas cooktop. Very nice staff.  Cozy Jacuzzi tucked in a private spot. Other than no elevator the ONLY downside with this room was the incredible noise level from the room adjoining. Although there is more than 6"of space to install insultation between the rooms it has not been done.  Creating a double door to enter each room is how I've seen it done effectively.  More secure for guests not adjoining as I was.  Beach cruisers provided free to ride to restaurants.< /text>

< Review>
I can not say enough good things about Hotel California. My husband stumbled upon it right before Labor Day weekend and they just happened to have one room left. We booked it and headed out.
Adults only so no worry about children running around. If you have kids but need a break, this is the place. Each room has a kitchenette if not a full kitchen. There is a full kitchen (minus a stove) on site that you have access too with two grills. It‚Äôs nice because if you don‚Äôt feel like eating out you do have the option to cook. Bonus, Ralphs grocery store is just down the road!

The office staff is very friendly. They have no problem answering questions and drawing in the map for you. Want to hot tips on where to go? Ask one of them!

The pool is 24/7 they just ask that you keep your yap shut after 10pm. A lot of the rooms have unique things: Room 15 has its own cute private seating area, Room 2 has its on reserved pool lounges, another room has its own private balcony with grill etc.

Pool is heated and has some umbrellas over it so when it was 115¬∞ we didn‚Äôt know, between the shade and the misters it‚Äôs heaven.

Since discovering it we‚Äôve been multiple times! We‚Äôre back celebrating Christmas with my in-laws and we‚Äôve already reserved our room for next Labor Day weekend. So like I said, I can‚Äôt say enough good things about it. Come try it for yourself!<//Review>

< review>
We were on a road trip and we wanted to check out Palm Springs, and we were happy to get a reservation at the Hotel California (not that one). When we arrived we were greeted at the door by Larry, who led us into the office and gave us chilled beverages while we checked in. The grounds are beautiful, with lush, tropical foliage and misters which helped us to keep cool in the summer heat. Jay gave us a comprehensive tour and led us to our room which was supplied with snacks and cold water. The pool and hot tub area are equipped with unique shade umbrellas and are a great place to spend time relaxing. All of the rooms have an outside sitting area. We walked to a Mexican restaurant and had a great meal.  We would have liked to stay longer, but we had commitments down the road. When we checked out Larry gave us iced waters and even washed the bugs off our windshield! We would like to return when we have more time to enjoy the atmosphere at the Hotel California in Palm Springs.<//review>

Wow!

I was looking for something unique and I found that and then some!

10 stars< /Text>

<name>Logan Weight</name>< Review>
On a dark desert highway, cool wind in my hair
Warm smell of colitas, rising up through the air
Up ahead in the distance, I saw a shimmering light
My head grew heavy and my sight grew dim
I had to stop for the night.
There she stood in the doorway;
I heard the mission bell
And I was thinking to myself
'This could be heaven or this could be Hell'
Then she lit up a candle and she showed me the way
There were voices down the corridor,
I thought I heard them say
Welcome to the Hotel California
Such a lovely place (such a lovely place)
Such a lovely face.
Plenty of room at the Hotel California
Any time of year (any time of year) you can find it here
Her mind is Tiffany-twisted, she got the Mercedes bends
She got a lot of pretty, pretty boys, that she calls friends
How they dance in the courtyard, sweet summer sweat
Some dance to remember, some dance to forget
So I called up the Captain,
'Please bring me my wine'
He said, 'we haven't had that spirit here since nineteen sixty-nine'
And still those voices are calling from far away,
Wake you up in the middle of the night
Just to hear them say"
Welcome to the Hotel California
Such a lovely place (such a lovely place)
Such a lovely face.
They livin' it up at the Hotel California
What a nice surprise (what a nice surprise), bring your alibis
Mirrors on the ceiling,
The pink champagne on ice
And she said, 'we are all just prisoners here, of our own device'
And in the master's chambers,
They gathered for the feast
They stab it with their steely knives,
But they just can't kill the beast
Last thing I remember, I was
Running for the door
I had to find the passage back to the place I was before
'Relax' said the night man,
'We are programmed to receive.
You can check out any time you like,
But you can never leave!'< /Review>

<Review>Hotel California is a wonderful place to stay. The staff are really helpful and lovely. The rooms are cute and clean. < username>
Gavin Maliska<//username>
<pictures>None<//pictures>< text>
My wife and I reunited with two other couples at the Hotel California in early February. We had a great time in a beautiful hotel. Larry and the staff were all welcoming, friendly and accommodating. One couple had the townhouse, with lots of extra space to hang in. Another had a room with a kitchen, where we gathered frequently. My wife and I had a standard room, which was clean, comfortable and roomy. Even though the temperature got a little brisk for a couple of days, the pool was warm and the spa was warmer. This hotel is conveniently located, quiet (we made it noisier), with a beautiful courtyard, great sitting areas, a nice kitchen with coffee and fruit every morning and facilities to make your own meal. It's small enough to offer that boutique feel and for every guest to know the staff. This was our second trip to Hotel California, and we'll be back.<//text>

< username>
Rennie<//username>
<Date>1482781919847<//Date>< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<Review>If you are looking for a small family-run hotel in Palm Springs, look no further. This is the place! We booked online while looking for a place to stay in Palm Springs, and wanted to avoid the standard resort hotel. We didn‚Äôt know what to expect when we arrived, but we soon felt that we had moved in with long-lost family: Larry, Jay, Lucy, Betty, and Mike. What an amazing crew! They made you feel welcome and waited-upon, without any being overbearing. (Seriously, we wish our relatives were like this!) The hotel itself is small, only 12 rooms, clean, with well-appointed efficiency units, surrounding a garden courtyard and pool, all with a touch of California funkiness. There is a large common kitchen off the courtyard where you could hang out and share a cup of coffee with guests or staff as you might wish. For those of you who have travelled in Europe, this felt like the California incarnation of the small family hotel. It couldn't have been better!< /Review><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< resp>
None<//resp>

<Rating>5<//Rating><Review>Hotel California is the quintessential retro hotel and classic Palm Spring experience.  We stayed at there on May 21 & 22, 2014.  We loved the accommodations and found the service exceptional.  Curly, the hotel manager, is well versed in the art of hospitality.  He was a lot of fun and made our stay comfortable and relaxing.  The staff overall was extremely helpful and friendly and went out of their way to accommodate our vacation needs. The rooms are cute and roomy and very clean.  The pool is on the smaller side but the common area surrounding the pool were gorgeous with plants and flowers and various seating areas and were extremely well maintained. <UserId.>106413824479387711294< /UserId.><username>Will Palmer</username><time>1429584449610<//time><rating>5</rating><review>Well, I had a terrible experience despite what the stars say (it is a five star hotel in my mind, but it was not a great experience, at least initially.) So here's the story: I was on a dark desert highway, with cool wind in my hair, and the highway smelled like colitas. I didn't know medical marijuana was legal, and it detracted from the environment.  Anyway, I saw a light in the distance it was, really, sort of a shimmering light. My eyes grew tired, and I needed to stop for the night.
There was a very attractive lady in the doorway when I checked in. She showed me to my room with a candle as a light (you need to update your lights, people.) The other guests at the hotel in the corridor said "Hey, Welcome to the Hotel California. It really is such a lovely place." Other guests seemed to express interest in the attractive hostess, and some guests were often found dancing in the courtyard. I then called up the captain and said "Please bring me my wine." He said "We haven't had that spirit here since 1969." I was confused. Wine wasn't a spirit.
The people sang in the night, and it woke me up and did not make for a pleasurable sleeping experience. There were unsettling mirrors on the ceiling (baked your room like an oven.) There was also pink champagne (pink champagne but no wine?) and the hotel administration trying to eat meat raw, by stabbing a beast. The shrieks were annoying. The hostess told me, somewhat cynically, "We are all just prisoners here of our own device."
The last thing I remember, I was heading for the door. I had to get back to the place I was before. The night man was friendly to the guests, but he said "Relax. We are programmed to receive. You can check out anytime you like, but you can never leave."
I exploited this loophole and checked out. Now I get a free hotel room and they can't kick me out!  It was all worth it, and this new prison is awesome! Five Stars!< /review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Response>
None<//Response>

<Gmap_id>0x80db1b13fcc165ef:0x1aab09af16cb60c< /Gmap_id><text>I don't normally write reviews online but my wife and I had such a great experience at the Hotel California that I am just compelled to share what a great group of people run this place and what a place this is.  We stayed in room #3 (of 14 if I  recall correctly) and it was a perfect little getaway studio. It was close to the hot tub (about 25-30 feet away) and only a few more feet away from the pool (partial pool view).  I can't say enough about Lucy and her Dad (Larry).  They really made us feel welcome and became a big part of making our 1-night getaway special.  We didn't get to take the free limo ($5 tip per person each way suggested) since we were running late for dinner and the limo service was only available until 10pm (which is understandable).  You also need to know that besides hardworking and customer oriented they are honest - I left my wallet in one of the night stand drawers and didn't realize it until 8 hours after checking out.  Lucy gave me a call only an hour after leaving (but I missed it) and she sent me an email to let me know.  Unfortunately we were 40 miles away by the time I returned her call so she suggested that she would just mail my wallet back to me (and wouldn't accept a reward).  Needless to say the Hotel California holds a very special place in our hearts as does the staff.  If you're looking for a quiet place to enjoy some alone time in a quaint place with lots of character and ambiance...you've found this jewel. < review>
Absolutely Delightful

We are really pleased to have found Hotel California. This is a delightful place to explore beautiful Palm Springs from. The service is great - we were offered a glass of wine to relax the moment we reached. The staff were super helpful and friendly.

We stayed two nights. Even though we had to switch rooms (from Room 7 to Room 3) because the hotel was full, it was no hassle.

Loved that there is a full kitchen and BBQs at the hotel as well. Great to be able to whip up some of our own food rather eat out all the time. Hotel California provides all the condiments for the cooking one needs. A Ralph's supermarket is nearby for one to buy all the food needed for cooking.

Hotel California does not provide breakfast but there's always fresh fruit, bread, and coffee / tea available in the kitchen. We make our own sandwiches for brekkie - simple with the toaster and griddle.

There's also a guest lounge / shared living room area with over 300 DVDs for those who want to stay in. You can watch the DVDs in your own room too.

What more can one ask for? :)</review>

< rate>
4< /rate>
< Date>
1601021099615< /Date>
<text>Happy houuuuurrr

Well since I'm going on week seven of having no new cases at work (and therefore no income), I'm starting to get a lot more excited about the happy hour deals around LA. I'd like to keep going out to eat, but I'd also like to continue to afford rent.

I've had this place bookmarked for a while, and one morning as I was getting my car washed, my housemate asked me to find a place for us to eat where we could take her dog. Scrolling through the options as the soapy water ran down my windows, I came upon this cute little restaurant that was a bit of a drive but had beer, food, and a patio. That was all we needed.

She had some errands to run first so I arrived about thirty minutes before her and sat at the bar. To my delight I discovered that I had arrived just after happy hour started, and that they have a pretty decent happy hour menu.

I started off with a beer that I finished once she arrived, and then I got a happy hour cocktail. I don't remember the name of it, just that it had elderflower as an ingredient.

The only thing that I didn't like about this place was how comically small the patio was. It was seriously the width of two adults standing shoulder to shoulder, and the length of one side of the building(which isn't too large). There weren't more than five tables and two bars squished back there, and just barely enough room for her husky under the table.

Our server was so sweet though! He brought out water and dog treats for her dog and the treats came on a little plate with a napkin. I was surprised how little I felt that I needed to call the server for something, considering we were in the corner on the patio. He was so attentive and just seemed like a really nice person.

I ordered the turkey burger from the HH menu (mostly because it came with fries) and it was actually pretty good. I would order it again, and definitely recommend it to anyone who would like poultry over red meat.

My housemate got a beer, chili cheese fries (with bacon jam!) and a chili cheese dog. Honestly I don't know how she stays so thin. I tried some of the fries with the jam and it was delicious.

We also decided to use the check in offer and split the bread pudding. It was the perfect end to a great lunch--though next time I'd try it with the whiskey ice cream rather than the vanilla.

5/5, will certainly return.<//text>< pics>
None</pics>

<user>110028909031632399683<//user><username>Michelle Klein-Hass<//username><Time>1525370698440< /Time><rate>5</rate>< Review>
A Cemita is a Torta (Mexican sandwich) with attitude. Traditionally served without meat, the better to complete your sandwich with freshly grilled meats from food vendors, they are a tradition of the Southern Mexican State of Puebla. You can get a "Traditional" which is a great lacto-vegetarian meal, or get yours with any number of meats featured. I have had Pollo Adobada, which is marinated grilled chicken, Milanesa de Pollo which is fried chicken, and the surprisingly good grilled salmon. Everything is fresh here. And Mexican Futbol (Soccer) matches are always on. Suggestion, BYO Swiss army knife if you have kids or light eaters, they don't cut these huge sandwiches in two for you.< /Review>

<userid>110489325411739328643<//userid><user_name>Morgan Fillion< /user_name><Time>1554527779815<//Time>< rating>
5</rating>
<Review>I love this place. A friend introduced me to Don Adrian's a few years back and every few months I get a craving for their cemitas. I pretty much have a standard order; a barbacoa cemita and a fish cemita. I like them best with the jalapeno and string cheese. It's a small store with 3 benches so we usually don't eat there. If you pay with a card there's a small fee so if that's an issue bring cash. The cemitas are about $10 each. If you pay by card, there is no way to add a tip so be aware. < Review>
I would rate it 10 stars because it is absolute perfection. Everything was phenomenal. The energy, the customer service, the music, the atmosphere, and the Sugar! It was indeed a perfect restaurant save the limited menu.

I can't really fault them for the menu. They did their best despite having limited items. My wife told the server that it was my birthday but I was diabetic, she still found a way to bring me a dessert that I could eat a little bit of!

I know I'm into minority so someone else will probably give him five stars. My only knock was that I don't like the way they made the hot wings. I know my taste are particular and not in a majority. I do promise everything else was perfect. It's a perfect place to take your friends, family, people visiting for out of town, business meetings, anything, anybody that just wants to have fun.</Review>

<Rate>4< /Rate>< time>
1621127855449</time>
<text>I've been to this location twice in the past 2 months. The first time, there was no indoor dining and the second time (today) was limited indoor seating.

RAVES: really friendly and accommodating staff (one of the times we were there one of our guests wanted to move to a different table and they did it, no problem, despite being busy; and today a server was just going around setting up the umbrellas for all outdoor tables), easy check in (we had reservations both times ; we waited a little both times to be seated but they text you when your table is ready so you can walk around if you want), yummy milk shakes and drinks, good food, and fun atmosphere.

RANTS:. While I watch them do a great job of wiping down tables before seating them...the outdoor area needed a little love.  The seat covers were dirty, the floor and carpets were very dirty/sticky, and the tables have little slots that were full of food and dirt than fell in and was either stuck or not cleaned out.

Knowing a lot of places are short staffed, the "rants" area may be situational.  One thing I'd recommend to Sugar Factory is investing in handhelds or iPad minis so servers can enter orders at the table. Because the drink menu is extensive, and some drinks can be labor intensive, it may help to have them entered at the table instead of servers having to write it down and go stand in line at a POS. Not to mention most parties are larger for celebrating. This can save time so servers can attend to other tables and customers may have shorter wait times.

I DO recommend this place though, especially for a special occasion, it's a great location!!!!  I'd recommend going either during the week or before 2pm on weekends and make a reservation üòÅüòÅüòÅ<//text><user_id>103238338314712182117< /user_id><pics>None<//pics><response>None<//response><GmapID>0x80c2bb8c8c000001:0xa792c16503a23529</GmapID>< Name>

< text>
My bestfriend & I came to Sugar Factory in LA tonight as part of our #BestieTrip and it was a great experience from beginning to end! The vibe & ambiance was great, very upbeat, fun, & lively. They are quite busy so it may take a little longer to be seated but it is well worth the wait because the food & drinks are delicious! We had the sampler platter, the Signature burger meal, & a cotton candy cosmopolitan drink - it all tasted amazing! Well worth the price. Our waitress Tiffany, who was also the manager, was very sweet, accommodating, efficient, & friendly. Would definitely recommend coming here!</text>

<Rate>4<//Rate>< text>
Everything is everything! There's a reason why Drake, Mariah Carey, Jenn Lopez and a host of other celebs dine here!  Great fun for kids and for adults!!! The place is da bomb!!! The staff - particularly the dynamic, charming, AWESOME so 'real' MARCUS -  is so cordial, so personable, so likable and so authentic! You can tell when you're meeting the real persona and when you're meeting the "gimme a good tip' persona. Marcus is authentically cool! The other team members were also sweet, patient, and professional as well as eager to please, helpful, and knowledgeable. These guys are definitely invested in customer service and quality service to the point that they make you wonder whether they own stock in the Company! Lol Maybe they do.

Sugar Factory's food staples don't disappoint in taste, but it's more about well-crafted, artistic presentation and colorfully stunning 3-D culinary art when it comes to amazing fare that turns heads and makes you feel the uniqueness of eating here!!! The ambiance is special, and the music so ideally compatible with the upbeat positivity and charisma of this dining experience. We kept wanting to order every eye-catching dish and drink that passed our table on a server's platter. The waffles we ordered (kid size order) were good. The eggs were fresh. I am always criticizing eggs served at many establishments I visit on the basis that the dish tastes stale, bland, mass-produced. I really liked the well-prepared eggs served at SF though. The cheeseburger was delectable as was the side salad with arugula onions cucumbers and other very fresh veggies. The drinks...amazing! Order the Diamond Rose! The visual alone wowed me! The elaborate yellow rose wall at reception makes an excellent background for pics btw and many selfie-taking patrons (families, couples, singles alike) take full photo opp advantage of the pretty decor!!! Love this place - Drake, Mariah and I!</text>

<user_id>116147530177147244777<//user_id>< name>
Naji Williams</name>
<date>1616960053182< /date>< rating>
4< /rating>
< Review>
The menu is a little pricey for what is essentially a kids' dream restaurant, BUT the service is deserving of high remarks. Our server interacted well with our kids and went as far as to show them some of the dances he learned from Tik Tok, which our kids loved.

This was my and our son's first time eating here (my wife and daughter had a lunch date a few weeks prior), and the food was pretty good. I had an Asian-inspired chicken salad (I apologize, I don't remember the name of it) that was not quite as large as the bigger Cheesecake factory salads, but was still a good size and left me feeling full after finishing the entire thing. The kids enjoyed sharing the multi-colored sliders and one of the specialty drinks (sans alcohol), and of course the various assorted candies adorning the huge glass it was served in. My wife had the chicken and waffles, which were also good (not Thumbs Up Diner in Atlanta good, but still pretty good for SoCal).

All in all, if you're looking for a fun family or even date night experience, you could do much worse than The Sugar Factory. The views from the outdoor deck add a nice touch as well. Oh, and the birthday celebrations that the staff puts on are pretty entertaining.

Give this place a try, especially if you have young ones; they'll love it.</Review>

< Text>
I loved the place however service is very slow. My server had a section with a party size of 20 plus people. We hardly seen her however she was polite. My second round of drinks took 45 mins to be brought out which was frustrating along with another 45 for our check . My food was delicious and so was my drink however my first choices I was told were not in stock. My next pet peeve was the umbrellas falling over multiple time. My particular umbrella had no sand bags or weights and spilled my drink which was never replaced due to my server never coming around. For $39 bucks thats very expensive to have spilled on my table due to my umbrella falling on it . I was not able to speak to a manager because no one came to check on us or offer help until after our meals and drinks were finished. I was livid and just wanted to leave. The tables cleanliness was also questionable and  the bathrooms were just plane nasty. No seat covers or toilet paper made me feel disgusted. I have a long list of complaints  from here that should be compensated but the lack of service got the best of my mood to where I wanted to just leave. Overall the actual place and concept is nice. Food was delicious but do not be in a rush service is slower than snail mail , and poor customer service.<//Text>

Might as well use all this free time to do something productive while waiting for a server, such as like warn others to avoid this restaurant. If you're just coming for a dessert, it may be worthwhile. For food though, it took 25 minutes to get a water, 1 hour to get food, and still waiting (15 minutes+) for a box and the check.

< text>
Slowwww service. We had reservations at 6pm, didn't get drink orders until 6:20pm (we only ordered water) and didn't our food until an hour later. Plus an additional 15+ minutes to get to-go boxes and the check. I also ordered a non-alcoholic "Virginia Strawberry Lemonade" that never came. The food was mediocre. I ordered soup and it came without a spoon. We had to ask 2 different people for a spoon only to be forgotten or ignored.

If you go for their desserts and alcohol, it might be worth while but only because it's "Instagrammable." Otherwise, it's not worth the high price.

Also, I wish they're stricter on their face mask requirements. There was a big party near us that kept walking all over the patio without masks.< /text>

< time>
1625168360645</time>
<text>I normally don't review car dealerships but I felt this one was necessary.

Let me start off by saying that my overall personal interaction with the salesperson working was pleasant, not pushy, and relatively transparent.

I feel the salesman wasn't familiar with Jeep's which I can understand, it's hard to know every car make and model front to back, so I don't discredit his efforts. He was generally very nice and pleasant.

My complaint with this company is they're selling this particular 10+ year old Jeep Wrangler Sahara for  $4k-$6k more than the blue book priced value.

The other issues above this ^ are as follows:

Upon inspecting the vehicle, the appearance is polished which I can tell they made this car appealing to the buyer. However, it quickly became a smoke and mirror situation.

Popped the hood and the radiator cap was missing.
Red flag.
The back seats were also removed from this vehicle, which the salesperson did offer to go to the Junk yard and find some for me.

The car sounded like it was idling ok.
The aftermarket off-roading tires were at 40% tread which for me, would be an additional $600+ to replace them, you cannot just buy 2 tires on a 4-wheeling vehicle. Another expense.

The car seems to ride ok, whoever had it before made the differential much More dramatic for crawling, so the steering was extremely loose even on city roads.

Took this baby on the freeway to see how she did, I had to flinstone my foot to the ground to even get it to go above 60mph, took time and effort. Then the entire car began shaking tremendously, it felt like it was going to fall apart. Yes, that's an exaggeration but it was pretty bad.

The car then coming to a stop, I had to slam all my energy into the breaks to get it to stop, meaning the breaks had a malfunction or have not been refreshed for resale.

After this scary test drive, I then drop it off at the lot where I went to roll up the driver side window. Which, would to my surprise not roll up.

The lot assistant said he informed his tech guy and that there's a way to get it up but it's a sweet spot.
I drove by this morning, that window is still down (I live a few blocks away).

The reason why I'm going into detail is because Had I not known what to look for, I may have purchased what appeared to be a cool great car, and then been  stuck with a 10 year old car that needs constant upgrades and repairs.

This car also says " CLEAN TITLE" but when you review the car auto report it has had structural damage twice which means, no! It's likely a salvaged title.

To anyone who is young or inexperienced with purchasing cars. Please take someone with you who can look out for these things, I've made this mistake as a kid and don't want someone to be sold a car that's not worth it's value like this. Good luck.</text><user_id>105136467200442375755<//user_id>< rate>
2<//rate>

<UserId.>113321117875544945837< /UserId.><Name>Spencer Hom</Name>< date>
1528641851458< /date>
<Rate>2< /Rate>< text>
This is a fairly sized taco shop, with a standard menu of items. Prices are pretty fair, although it is cash only. Service was alright, nothing special.

I decided on the breakfast burrito, which contains eggs, potato, rice, beans, cheese and bacon or ham. I was pretty disappointed by this burrito, it was very dry and the eggs were pretty overcooked. Their red salsa was also lacking in flavor and spice to say the least.

Overall, this place just has low average food, but it's not somewhere I would want to revisit.</text>

2<//rating>
<review>This place is super convenient to my house so when I've craved a burrito or carne asada quesadilla and don't want to drive more than 5 mins, Chito's got the job done.  I usually order over the phone, but found myself ordering from the register today.  I looked at the menu and ordered the quesadilla supreme with carne asada (pick looked like the carne asada quesadilla I typically ask for on the phone).  Have to add guacamole to it (weird for a "supreme"), and it comes out to like $9 (steep), but it's what I'm in the mood for.  When my food comes out, it's filled with beans, which is not my thing at all.  I look at the menu and there's no mention of beans (wouldn't even think to ask on a quesadilla), and ask for them to remake it without.  No dice.  I'll need to buy another $9 quesadilla.  I say that I've been coming for years and I will absolutely never come back out of principle.  Woman at the register didn't flinch at all.  A second woman said that she would grab her boss, but after waiting around for a bit, it was clear no one was interested in making it right.  I forgave their "cash only" stubbornness for a while, but I'm officially done.< /review>< Pics>

<Resp>None< /Resp><Text>Appalling and horrendous.  That's the only way to describe my experience.  Yesterday, as I was riding my bike past Dr. Domotor's around 4:45pm, I noticed that there was a dead parrot in the grass in front of the "Animal Hospital".  I figured some low-life that couldn't be bothered to properly dispose of it had left it there to make it another person's problem.  Well, it became mine.

I went inside and told the lady at the front desk that there was a dead parrot outside of the building.  When she looked at me like she didn't know what to do, I offered to bring it inside if she gave me a box and a pair of gloves.  A lady came out in scrubs, and the first lady asked her if she would take care of it.  Her response was "I'm off the clock.  Can't you call Animal Control?"  The first lady then thanked me for telling them and assured me they would take care of it.

Well, I guess everyone was off the clock.  They didn't do anything, not even call Animal Control.  In this case, that would be the Pasadena Humane Society and SPCA.  I called them this morning after I walked past the building and the bird was still there.  When I called Dr. Domotor's to let them know what happened, I didn't even get a response, they just hung up on me without saying anything.

To make it clear, I would have been willing to take care of the bird myself in other circumstances.  Years ago, driving past a restaurant I worked at (on my day off), I noticed a dead cat in the road in front of the building.  I stopped, borrowed a shovel, and buried the cat away from the building.  Had I not, there's no telling how long it would have been there.  It's also less likely that the litter of kittens with her, which were still alive, would have been saved.  I don't usually carry a shovel on my bike, and I wasn't about to put a dead parrot in my pocket so I could rub it with my thumb like Lenny Small.

I also understand that you might be wary about a dead animal, and want to take certain precautions before exposing it to other animals.  There is absolutely no excuse for just leaving a dead animal in front of an "Animal Hospital" overnight, or even for ten minutes.  Perhaps at least somebody there has a brain and genuine concern for animals, but at least three don't.  If you take your pets there, good luck with the ones that end up handling them.<//Text>< Date>
1393551699949</Date>

<user>115908874269648500961<//user><Name>Brooks Keys< /Name><date>1326839930107<//date><rating>1< /rating><text>Domotor's Doggie Dachau

I left my 10 1/2 year old spayed Lab for three nights kenneling.  I took two standard bed pillows in sewn-together cases, a cotton throw rug that goes on top of the pillows, and in a large zip-lock a T-shirt I'd worn to provide my scent, a squeaky toy, and several large crunchy bones. I verbally asked them to place the pillow in her kennel and to give the dog the T-shirt, squeaky toy, and one crunchy bone per day.  The assistant acknowledged this.  The vet's assistant removed my dog's collar and scarf and gave them to me, saying they could be a choke hazard.  (It's the first time I'd had this occur for kenneling - there must have been a tragic experience in the past, but better safe than sorry)  I inspected the individual kennel my dog was in.  It was very clean and had a clean blanket on the concrete floor.  I was not allowed to open the gate and place the pillows inside, but was assured my dog would have them.

After the three nights I returned for my dog.  The dog was as healthy as when I left her.  I put her collar back on and asked for the pillows, T-shirt, etc. In a jiffy the assistant returned with the pillows, rug, and zip-lock.  The zip-lock contained the T-shirt, squeaky toy, and ALL of the crunchy bones.  The T-shirt, pillows, and rug had no dog hair on them.

I highly suspect that my pure bred, ACK-papers, house-dog had to sleep on a blanket over concrete with nothing to remind her of 10 1/2 years with her owner, or hope that she would be reunited with me.  My dog is healthy and Dr. Domnotor's kennel is very clean.  I have no complaint about the safety or sanitation of the kennels.  But I think I sent my dog to a Doggy Dachau.  She will not be kenneled there again.< /text>< pictures>

< text>
My mom has been going to Dr Demotor for 15 years. We moved during that time and have tried new vets that are closer. Every time we try a new vet we end up taking the animal back to Dr. Demotor because the other vets don't have the experience or knowledge about taking care of tricky issues. I have a cat who got into a fight. I tried taking her to VCA and they didnt find the puncture wounds. Because they didnt find the wounds the first time bacteria festered under her skin and now, a week later, she is loosing almost half of the skin on her back. The doctors at Dr Domotors office decided to take a skin culture to be sure that we were fighting the disease with the right antibiotics. No to mention they remembered to give me painkillers... Yea Dr. Domotor is expensive but it's a sure way to guarantee that your pet will get proper treatment by experienced professionals. < Review>
I really love Angel Maid Bakery. We recently got our daughter's first birthday cakes from there. Did I mention we got five different kinds? Yes, we got five! :)

Instead of having one large sheet cake we got two marble custards (our favorite), two fresh strawberries (fan favorite) and chocolate dobash. The marble and the chocolate both have custard and it's so delicious. Delicious as in refreshing, creamy and oh so tasty.

We normally buy all our cakes from there and do they a great job every time we order from them. It's hard not to resist some cream puffs while you are there too, which is also so good! Everything is so good!

Delicious cakes with great people who work there and very affordable. I love Angel Maid. Love!<//Review>
